sentence-detokenized: CRICKET - LEICESTERSHIRE TAKE OVER AT THE TOP AFTER INNINGS WIN.
West Indies all-rounder Phil Simmons made four for 38 on Friday as Leicestershire beat Somerset by an innings and 39 runs in two days to take over the lead in the county championship.

Their stay at the top may be short-lived, however, as title rivals Essex, Derbyshire and Surrey all came close to victory, while Kent made up for lost ground in their rain-affected match against Nottinghamshire.

After knocking Somerset out for 83 on the first morning at Grace Road, Leicestershire extended their first innings by 94 runs before being bowled out for 296, with Andy Caddick, who had been sent to England, taking three points for 83.
Somerset got off to a solid start in their second inning with 213 points before Simmons came in and got them out for 174 points.
Essex, however, look set to regain their top spot after Nasser Hussain and Peter Such gave them a solid grip on their match against Yorkshire at Headingley.
Hussain, considered surplus to England's one-day matches, scored 158, his first championship hundred of the season, as Essex reached 372 and took a lead of 82 in the first innings.

By the end Yorkshire had turned it into a 37-run advantage, but off-spinner Such had dashed their hopes, taking four for 24 off 48 balls and leaving them hanging on for 119 for five and praying for rain.

At the Oval, Surrey captain Chris Lewis, another man dumped by England, continued to silence his critics as he followed up his four for 45 on Thursday with 80 not out in Friday's match against Warwickshire.
He was well backed by English hope Mark Butcher, who made 70 as Surrey finished with 429 for seven, a lead of 234.

Derbyshire continued the chase for their first championship title since 1936 by reducing Worcestershire to 133 for five in their second innings, which was still 100 runs from avoiding defeat in the innings.
Australian Tom Moody took six for 82, but Chris Adams, 123, and Tim O'Gorman, 109, took Derbyshire to 471 and a lead of 233 in the first innings.
After the frustration of seeing the opening day of their match badly affected by the weather, Kent kicked it up a gear and got Nottinghamshire down 214 points.
They were held up by a brave 84 from Paul Johnson, but former England fast bowler Martin McCague took four for 55.
At stumps Kent had reached 108 for three.

FOOTBALL - SHEARER APPOINTED CAPTAIN OF ENGLAND.
The world's most expensive footballer Alan Shearer was named the new England captain on Friday.
The 26-year-old, who joined Newcastle for £15 million ($23.4 million), takes over from Tony Adams, who led the team at the European Championships in June, and former captain David Platt.
Adams and Platt are both injured and will miss England's first World Cup qualifier against Moldova on Sunday.
Shearer takes over the captaincy on a trial basis, but new coach Glenn Hoddle said he saw no reason why the former Blackburn and Southampton striker should not make the post his own.
"I'm sure there will be no problem, I'm sure Alan is the man for the job," said Hoddle.
"There were three or four people who could have done it, but when I spoke to Alan, he was ready for it and really wanted it.
"In four days it's very difficult to come to a 100 percent conclusion on something like this...
but he knows how to behave, his teammates respect him and he knows the team's situation, even if he plays up front. "
Shearer's Euro 96 striker Teddy Sheringham withdrew from the squad on Friday with an injury.
He is likely to be replaced by Shearer's Newcastle teammate Les Ferdinand.

Romania beat Lithuania 2-1 (half-time 1-1) in their European U21 football match on Friday.
FOOTBALL - ROTOR FANS LOCKED OUT AFTER VIOLENCE IN VOLGOGRAD.

Rotor Volgograd must play its next home game behind closed doors after fans threw bottles and stones at Dynamo Moscow players during Saturday's 1-0 home defeat that ended Rotor's brief spell as the league's top team.
The head of the Russian league's disciplinary committee, Anatoly Gorokhovsky, said Friday that Rotor would play against Lada Togliatti in front of empty stands on September 3.
The club that knocked Manchester United out of last year's UEFA Cup was fined $1,000.
Despite the defeat, Rotor is well placed with 11 matches remaining in the championship.
The Volgograd team is three points behind Alania and two behind Dynamo Moscow, but has a game in hand over the leaders and two over the Moscow club.
BOXING - ROBERTO DURAN FROM PANAMA FIGHTS AGAINST THE SANDS OF TIME.
Panamanian boxing legend Roberto "Hands of Stone" Duran takes to the ring on Saturday in another age-defying attempt to continue his long career.
Duran, 45, takes on little-known Mexican Ariel Cruz, 30, in a non-title super middleweight bout in Panama City.
The match, Duran's first on home soil in 10 years, is billed here as "the return of the legend", and Duran still talks as if he were in his prime.
I'm not going to retire," Duran told Reuters.

But those close to the boxer acknowledge that the man who has won championships in four different weight classes - light heavyweight, welterweight, junior middleweight and middleweight - is nearing the end of his career.
"Every time he fights, he is on the last frontier of his career.
If he loses on Saturday, it could devalue his position as one of the world's best boxers," said Panamanian Boxing Federation president Ramon Manzanares.
Duran, whose 97-12 record spans three decades, hopes a win in the 10-round fight will earn him a rematch against Hector "Macho" Camacho of Puerto Rico.
Camacho took a controversial points decision against the Panamanian in Atlantic City in June in a title fight.

TENNIS - TARANGO AND O'BRIEN CREATE TWO SURPRISES UNDER THE LIGHTS.
Andre Agassi escaped disaster on Thursday, but Wimbledon finalists MaliVai Washington and Marcelo Rios were not so lucky on a night of surprises at the US Open.

The 11th-seeded Washington was unable to repeat his miracle comeback at Wimbledon as he lost to red-hot wildcard Alex O'Brien 6-3 6-4 5-7 3-6 6-3 6-3 in a two hour and 51 minute match on Stadium Court.
Next door in the stands, 10th seed Rios lost to another player with a Wimbledon connection, bad boy Jeff Tarango.
The temperamental left-hander defeated the Chilean 6-4 4-6 7-6 6-2.
Today's programme went smoothly, although sixth-seeded former champion Agassi had to wriggle out of a dangerous 3-6 0-4 hole after winning 18 of the last 19 games against India's Leander Paes.
But the night belonged to the new players.
Washington, who came back from a 1-5 deficit to trail by two sets in the third set against Todd Martin in the Wimbledon semi-finals, looked set for another sensational comeback.
O'Brien, who two weeks ago won his first professional title in New Haven, served to 5-4 in the third set before Washington came back.
"I just kept saying to myself: "Keep giving yourself the best chance to win, keep fighting and maybe something will happen," said the 26-year-old O'Brien, who is ranked 65th.
"I kept my head and I was proud of myself for that - normally I would have folded up the tent and gone home."
The hard-working O'Brien, a former US college national champion, made 17 aces to eventually subdue the never-say-die Washington.
The fifth set remained on serve until the sixth game when Washington, after saving a break point with a forehand winner down the line, netted a backhand point to give O'Brien a 4-2 lead.
The Texan sent in two aces to hold serve at 5-2 and then took advantage of his eighth match point to win when Washington found the net with another backhand from 40-0.
"You just keep fighting and trying to get him to play a bit.
I think he got a little tense at a few points," Washington said."
But I think he served pretty well when he had to. "

Tarango, whose tantrum at Wimbledon two years ago earned him a $28,000 fine and an exclusion from this year's All-England Club tournament, chanted and taunted fans during his lively two-hour and 24-minute tango with Rios in the stands.
A loud cheering section supported the distracted Chilean and booed the frail American, who was soaking up all the attention.
"I'm an emotional player," said Tarango, who is ranked 104. "
I thought I played very well tonight, very focused. "
The match was decided in the third set, which the American won 7-5 to the dismay of the crowd.
"I love the audience, even if they boo me every day.
It gives me energy and makes me play my best tennis," Tarango said.
"I played some of my best tennis in college when the fraternities threw beer at me.
If tennis was like that every day, I think everyone would have a lot more fun if it was. "
"He always complains too much," Rios said. "
But I don't think it is.
I thought I played really badly.
It was difficult to play at night.
I lost too many points, which I never lose.
"I don't see the ball as I see it during the day.
I play an American, so that's why I play at night.
I didn't feel good on the field. "
At the end of the match, Tarango blew sarcastic kisses to the crowd, then waved his body to Rios' cheerleaders in a mocking salute.
"I support their enthusiasm," Tarango said of the fans. "
At the same time, they openly cheer against me.
When I won, I thought I'd give them a little surprise. "
NFL AMERICAN FOOTBALL RANDALL CUNNINGHAM RETIRES.
Randall Cunningham, the National Football League's all-time leading rusher at quarterback and one of the most athletic players ever to line up over the middle, retired Thursday.
Cunningham played his entire 11-year career with the Philadelphia Eagles.
Cunningham has been selected to the Pro Bowl three times and rushed for 4,482 yards on 677 carries.
"I want to thank the Eagles organization and the wonderful fans in Philadelphia for supporting me throughout my career," Cunningham said.
"Although I'm sad to be leaving, I'm looking forward to spending more time with my family and pursuing other interests that have been on the back burner for a while."
"Randall was one of the most exciting quarterbacks in NFL history," said Eagles owner Jeffrey Lurie. "
During his 11 years in Philadelphia, Randall was the cornerstone of the Eagles' franchise and brought many great moments to fans in Philadelphia and throughout the NFL. "
Cunningham was selected in the second round in 1985 and completed 1,874 of 3,362 passes (55.7 percent) for 22,877 yards and 150 touchdowns.
Cunningham has already been signed as a broadcaster.
